37–1500":"1437–1500","1435–1495":"1435–1495","about 1470":"circa 1470","1495":"1495","1560":"1560","1461":"1461","1470":"1470","Cir 1460":"1460","1437":"1437","1546":"1546","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1478":"1478","1465":"1465","1541":"1541","1463":"1463","1474":"1474","1506":"1506","1537":"1537","Berkhamstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bovingdon, Hertfordshire,England":"Bovingdon, Hertfordshire, England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Berkampsted, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berkhampstead St. Mary, Hertfordshire, England":"Berkhamsted, Hertfordshire, England"},"en":{"1463–1506":"1463–1506","1461–1560":"1461–1560","1465–Male":"1465–Deceased","1474–1541":"1474–1541","1478–1537":"1478–1537","1468–1546":"1468–1546","1470–1522":"1470–1522","1437–1500":"1437–1500","1435–1495":"1435–1495","about 1470":"about 1470","1495":"1495","1560":"1560","1461":"1461","1470":"1470","Cir 1460":"1460","1437":"1437","1546":"1546","1435":"1435","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1522":"1522","1478":"1478","1465":"1465","1541":"1541","1463":"1463","1474":"1474","1506":"1506","1537":"1537","Berkhamstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bovingdon, Hertfordshire,England":"Bovingdon, Hertfordshire, England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Berkampsted, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkhampstead St. Mary, Hertfordshire, England":"Berkhamsted, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Axtell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Asketill</i>, from Old Norse <i>Ásketill</i>, composed of the elements <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’ (see also   Haskell  ). This name was in use both among Scandinavian settlers in eastern England (esp. Norfolk) and among the Normans.","nickname for a salt merchant or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>hakke-salt</i> ‘chop salt (into pieces)’. The development of the surname to <i>Axtel</i> is evidenced in 16th-century Hertfordshire and Buckinghamshire."],"variants":[{"name":"Axton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Axton in Kent, named from the Old English personal name <i>Acca</i> + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’.","(Buckinghamshire): possibly a variant of   Axtell  , or alternatively a habitational name from a metathesized form of a placename such as Ashton in Bainton, Northamptonshire, which is recorded as <i>Axton</i> in 1253."]},{"name":"Antell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Antil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Anketil</i>, a common Norman variant of Old Norse <i>Ásketill</i> (see   Axtell  ).","English: variant of   Antill  , a habitational name from Ampthill in Bedfordshire.","Swedish and Finnish (of Swedish origin): ornamental name from placenames in Finland and Sweden such as Ant(t)ila and Antby, or from the Finnish personal name <i>Antti</i> (a vernacular form of   Andreas  ), + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>."]},{"name":"Estell","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Eskell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Askell</i>, Old Norse <i>Áskell</i>, a shortened form of <i>Ásketill</i> (see   Axtell  ). The personal name was also popular among the Normans, sometimes in the form <i>Anskell</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Ans-</i> substituted for <i>As-</i>), which largely explains why the name occurs in post-Conquest England in counties not settled by Vikings.","topographic name from Middle English <i>est</i> ‘east’ + <i>hal(le)</i> ‘chief building, hall’ or <i>hale</i> ‘nook, remote place’ (Old English <i>ēast</i> + <i>hall</i> or <i>halh</i>), denoting someone who lived or worked at the ‘east hall’ or who lived at a place known as the ‘east nook’."]},{"name":"Haskell","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Askell</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, from Old Norse <i>Áskell</i>, a shortened form of <i>Ásketill</i> (see   Axtell  ). The personal name was also popular among the Normans, sometimes in the form <i>Anskell</i> (with ancient Germanic <i>Ans-</i> substituted for <i>As-</i>), which explains why the name occurs in post-Conquest England in counties not settled by Vikings. Its appearance as a surname is often disguised by altered pronunciations; metathesis of /sk/ to /ks/, spelled <i>-x-</i>, for example, has given rise to   Axtell  . The Normans frequently used the name in Frankish forms; see   Askin  ,   Haskin  ,   Hasty  , and   Astin  . For the name in the Isle of Man see   Castell  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Khaskl</i>, a Yiddish form of the Hebrew name <i>Yeḥezqel</i> (see   Ezekiel  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Axtell was born in 1463, in Bovingdon, Hertfordshire, England, his father, Henry Axtell, was 26 and his mother, Cecily, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Gould. He died in 1506, in his hometown, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1463–1506":"1463–1506","1461–1560":"1461–1560","1465–Male":"1465–Surnud","1474–1541":"1474–1541","1478–1537":"1478–1537","1468–1546":"1468–1546","1470–1522":"1470–1522","1437–1500":"1437–1500","1435–149